<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="4cc7ab1a-86ba-5d20-a104-4e1dbe6dfba2" activityNameId="750d23da-b660-41bc-bad2-c73fe08ce292" parentActivityId="17ddc472-36d2-5136-ba64-e0bf3463e898" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">soybean production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">soya, soybean cultivation, soy production</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">This activity starts with soil cultivation after the harvest of the previous crop.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This dataset includes cultivation of the field prior to planting, field treatments, planting, applications of nutrients and pesticides, and harvest. It ends with harvested maize grain at the farm gate, prior to storage.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of soybean (fresh matter) in the US state of Iowa at farm, with a pre-drying moisture content of 13.1%. This dataset includes cultivation of the field prior to planting, field treatments, planting, applications of nutrients and pesticides, and harvest.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The average yield of soybean grown in Iowa for the 2014-2021 seasons was 3,793 kg/ha (wet mass) (USDA NASS 2021).  The dataset reflects the average soybean produced in Iowa from 2014 to 2021, inclusive, as that period allows for at least one value from USDA statistics for most parameters and generally three or more.  It reflects the mix of tillage practices (39% no till, 47% reduced till,  13% conventional tillage) (CTIC (2020a) )  and rotations (100% in rotation with maize) for soy bean.  About 95% of planted soybean is genetically engineered for herbicide tolerance (USDA NASS 2021). This dataset reflects practices consistent with that.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Area, productivity, use of mineral and organic fertilisers and pesticides, and irrigation inputs are based on farmer data reported to the U.S. Department of Agriculture. Because soybean is primarily grown in annual rotation with maize, lime use is based on soil pH and guidance from agricultural extension offices for maize cultivation and its application is associated with the maize production system; this dataset does not include lime application attributed to soybean. Field operations and equipment types and fuel use are based on materials provided to growers by the agricultural extension office(s), including farm budgets, and on survey information agricultural extension office(s) collect from growers, in conjunction with row spacing data from USDA.  Drainage (tile or ditch) is installed on 66.0% based on state-level agricultural survey data from USDA.  Irrigation is included based on share of crop irrigated (less than 0.5% over the time period, USDA NASS (2018)). Chemigation is included in this and is not treated as an additional operation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Area cultivated for soybean in Iowa decreased by 7% between 2000 and 2021 (USDA NASS data, 5 year rolling averages) The crop LCI tool allocates land use change to all crops and activities that grew in the last 20 years in the US, and only to them, according to their respective area increase; crops for which planted area decreased are not attributed LUC impacts or credits. Thus, the amount of Land use change, annual crop is zero for soybean grown in Iowa.The total cropland change 1997 to 2017 was 3.0% for all crops in Iowa (NRCS 2020a).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Soil characteristics (pH, clay, SOM, slope) are based on the Iowa soil survey (ISPAID). No anti-erosion practices are assumed in the dataset; instead, the erosion soil loss reported in the U.S. Natural Resources Conservation Service's Natural Resource Inventory is used.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References: USDA NASS (2021) Area, Production, Yield by State - Soybean - 2010-2021. US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agricultural Statistics Service. https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov (direct query: https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov/results/331F88CC-004E-34D2-B825-F8F65DAC7879)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">USDA NASS (2018) 2018 Irrigation and Water Management Survey  (2017 Census of Agriculture). US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.nass.usda.gov/Publications/AgCensus/2017/Online_Resources/Farm_and_Ranch_Irrigation_Survey/index.php</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">NRCS (2020a) Land Cover/use of non-Federal rural land, by State and year, in the 2017 National Resources Inventory. USDA, Natural Resources Conservation Service. http://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/NRCS_RCA/reports/nri_crop_nat.html, https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/portal/nrcs/rca/national/technical/nra/rca/text/#NRI%20Cropland</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">CTIC (2020a) OpTIS - Operational Tillage Information System. Conservation Technology Information Center (CTIC). https://www.ctic.org/optis_tabular_query accessed March 23, 2021</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Iowa Soil Survey &amp; Digital Soil Data: ISPAID. Version 8.1.1 (2017). https://www.extension.iastate.edu/soils/ispaid</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="e2e1f67d-3393-4182-86f6-1ada2f77c3e5">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">0111:Growing of cereals (except rice), leguminous crops and oil seeds</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="d38650a8-8c23-4941-9292-f9d7a4dce29b">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">US-IA</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Production of soy bean in Iowa (US-IA).</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset reflects current practice for soy bean in Iowa as of 2022.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2014-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The valid period covers 2014-01-01 through 2021-12-31 based on primary data sources. The production volumes, areas and applications are covered by data throughout the time period (annual for production and area, alternate years for applications). Due to disruption in 2020, some USDA data was reported for 2021 instead. Because the specific pesticides used show time-dependent trends, the most recent 3 years of data are used to avoid underweighting the most dominant pesticides currently used and to avoid skewing impacts based on compounds no longer in use. Field operations are based on current enterprise crop budgets and change little year to year.  Data for manure applications were only available for time periods prior to the valid period but represent the best available option.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
