      <intermediateExchange id="e362928f-cefb-5976-8802-9f18c889b529" unitId="86bbe475-8a8f-44d8-914c-e398787e7121" amount="3.99095402242138E-05" intermediateExchangeId="1d32b849-121f-4d23-853c-fa2bf55c42e9" activityLinkId="c43109a6-3690-5175-9675-9da99eed30e2">
        <name xml:lang="en">land use change, annual crop</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">ha</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Area cultivated for soybean in Iowa decreased by 7% between 2000 and 2021 (USDA NASS data, 5 year rolling averages) US NRCS data indicates that total cropland in Iowa has expanded over the same period by 3% (NRCS 2020a). The expansion of cropland for all crops in Iowa in this period was supplied 100% from CRP land 
Calculated value from ecoinvent Crop LCI tool, 0.15137 divided by the yield in kg/ha.  Land use change is allocated to all crops and activities that grew in the last 20 years for the US, and only to them, according to their respective area increase. Crop production and natural land areas in all countries use data from 1989 to 2012 (FAOSTAT 2012), as well as for country climates and soil types (EU-JRC 2010c). Crops for which planted area decreased are not attributed LUC impacts or credits.  Land use change (LUC) combines land transformation areas calculated with the adapted 'Direct Land Use Change Assessment Tool' version 2014 developed by Blonk Consultants and the carbon losses from soil organic carbon (SOC) and vegetation (VEG) as calculated in ecoinvent v3. See 'WFLDB-Guidelines.pdf', available at https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/File/Reports.</comment>
