      <intermediateExchange id="9befb17b-a6d5-5a3b-b39c-2430262225f2" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" amount="7.53148931196618E-06" intermediateExchangeId="aeb1ebef-7095-4956-91da-8c4017df556d" activityLinkId="01c5d2d7-ccd7-5963-9dad-6ca6fa18f33b">
        <name xml:lang="en">solid manure loading and spreading, by hydraulic loader and spreader</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">2.86E-2 kg/ha (7.53E-6 kg/kg soybean) solid manure loading and spreading, by hydraulic loader and spreader
The total effective manure application rate of 653 kg/ha (0.172 kg/kg soybean) is calculated from USDA ERS data for amount of manure applied (12.8 kg/ha; 0.17 kg/kg soybean) on share of crop area treated (5.1%)  (years available: 2002, 2006) USDA ARMS 2015. The manure data has significant uncertainty due to both the age of the available data and the statistical limitations imposed by confidentiality for USDA survey respondents.
About 40% of applied manure is in liquid form, calculated from the share of dry, semi-dry and slurry and lagoon manure applied  from ARMS data. USDA describes the liquid/slurry and dry manure shares as "Statistically unreliable due to a low sample size" (USDA ARMS 2015a). 55.9% of manure from cattle. 44.1% of manure from swine. Applied swine manure is assumed to be liquid only. USDA data shows zero share from poultry manure. Cattle manure is apportioned between solid and liquid consistent with USDA estimated shares after accounting for swine manure
The calculated solid and liquid manure shares in this dataset are thus 44.1% solid and 55.9% liquid manure. The effective application rates are 365.2 kg solid manure per ha (7.55E-5 kg/kg soybean) and .3 m3 liquid manure per ha (7.55E-5 m3/kg soybean).

Field operations are as identified in crop- and rotation-specific enterprise crop budgets supplied by the regional agricultural extension office and matched to equipment type in the budget or crop guidance.  (ISU Extension 2021; ISU Extension 2020a).  Operations are matched to equipment type and where multiple options are available, the share of each is determined from guidance and annual farmer survey data (Custom Rate Summaries) for contracted operations/equipment. Where an operation applies only to a portion of the harvested area, the number of passes has been scaled by the % of harvested area to which it applies (e.g., manure spreading or insecticide) as indicated by USDA statistics (applications) or USDA reports (manure use) or as otherwise indicated in enterprise crop budgets. 
Source(s): 
USDA ARMS (2015) Agricultural Resource Management Survey (ARMS) Farm Financial and Crop Production Practices: Manure Table, Corn. USDA. https://data.ers.usda.gov/reports.aspx?ID=17883 
Beegle D and Peters J. (2019) Common Manure Test Results Conversions. National Cooperative Extension Resource, Livestock And Poultry Environmental Learning Community (Lpelc). https://lpelc.org/common-manure-test-results-conversions/ accessed October 5, 2021
Wilson M (2021) Manure Characteristics. University of Minnesota Extension. https://extension.umn.edu/manure-management/manure-characteristics; https://drive.google.com/file/d/1-c8bx_75YSsQZTNFB_YFVD-uw_SbX1dB/view?usp=sharing 
ISU Extension 2020b
ISU Extension 2020c
ISU Extension 2020d</comment>
