      <elementaryExchange id="12cd07eb-7ab1-5cdc-881b-451341dd327e" unitId="eb955b7c-7bed-401f-9c76-5db716ca3640" amount="0.0122008076712198" elementaryExchangeId="c4a82f46-381f-474c-a362-3363064b9c33">
        <name xml:lang="en">Occupation, annual crop, irrigated</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">m2*year</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Land occupation per year (annual growing season).  Land is under rotation with other annual crop production (~80% corn-soy, ~20% corn-corn, Socolar et al 2021 ). US NRCS data indicates that total cropland in Iowa has expanded 3% over the last 20 years, met entirely by land idled under the Conservation Reserve Program (CRP) (NRCS 2020a), resulting in a flux to/from annual crop that is essentially steady state. 
Annual production is 17.9 million tonnes from US Department of Agriculture (USDA NASS) 2021a on 3.9 million ha planted and 10.9 million ha harvested. Thus occupation is 02.636 ha/t or 26364.672 m2/t (2.6.365m2/kg). This overall land use is split into irrigated (0.46%) and non-irrigated (99.54%) based on agricultural census data () (1.22E-2 m2 planted/kg harvested maize of irrigated land, and 2.62E+0 m2 planted/kg harvested maize of non-irrigated land).
Sources:</comment>
